title: For Sale:  12ga Tactical Shotgun
location: Goldsboro, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
This is a Tristar Cobra Force 12ga shotgun.  Has rubber molded pistol grip with full length stock, metal fully adjustable ghost ring sights, sight rail, red bright fiber optic guarded front sight, 20 inch barrel, barrel is threaded to accept Berretta style choke tubes, sling swivels, and has a magazine tube extension to bring it's capacity up to 8 rounds.

If you're looking for a tactical shotgun this is it.

The 20 inch barrel is only 2 inches longer than an 18 inch barrel so it can still be easily used for home defense.  Perfectly reliable as a pump action shotgun.  It has less than a case of ammo through it, but has had absolutely no issues at all and feels very solid and operates smoothly.  Doesn't have the wobbly feel that many other shotguns have when operating the pump.

What initially lead me to buy this shotgun was that it has a 20 inch barrel threaded to accept choke tubes.  It comes with a cylinder choke muzzle break/breaching break, but I bought a flush mount cylinder choke and a modified choke tube for it.  All 3 chokes come with it.  The 20 inch barrel gives much better velocity and patterning compared to an 18 inch barrel.  I patterned it side by side with a Remington 870 with a modified choke in an 18 inch barrel and this Tristar held a much better pattern out to 40 yards.  I have used it to shoot a round of sporting clays and the gun did not struggle at all when put to the challenge (would have done much better if the person behind it wasn't such a bad shot).

Looking to sell it with the red dot that's mounted on it, with the 3 choke tubes, and the magazine extension.  I know you can buy a Chinese made shotgun for $200 bucks, but it's not going to be as nicely made as this one.  Once you pick up the shotgun and feel how sturdy it is in your hands you'll understand why I'm asking $350 for the shotgun and everything that comes with it.

Texting is the best way to get ahold of me.  Email me if you're interested and I'll send you my cell phone number.  Already get enough junk calls, not going to post my phone number.

title: For Sale:  mossberg 190 16 gauge bolt action shotgun
postcontent:
200 OBO!

ssberg Model 190 - A Shotgun that can Kick Chuck Norris' Ass



Mossberg, vintage, bolt-action, shotgun, 1950s, Michigan Upland Hunting, 
Mossberg's amazing arm-lengthening Model 190
It's not often that a product comes along that is completely ground-breaking in its technology, and when it does, it draws attention. Sort of like everyone admiring an iPhone5, hunters constantly point towards my shotgun and say, "What the heck is that thing?"

"Why, it's a Mossberg model 190," I answer. "Thank you for asking."

It's hard to decide where to begin describing the many innovative features of the Mossberg model 190. From muzzle to butt, it screams "1950."  Actually, it was made from 1950 to 1955.

Let's start at the butt.  The butt of the beautifully matte-finished genuine walnut Monte Carlo one-piece pistol grip stock of this beauty is capped with a non-recoil-absorbing piece of the hardest plastic I've ever seen; quite possibly that 1950's miracle of polymerization, Bakelite.

The stock itself has such a plain finish that even dings, chips, or scratches do not diminish it. They only add to the gun's individuality.

Then there's the action. The engineers at Mossberg thought long and hard about how to improve a hunter's marksmanship before they decided that a bolt-action was the ticket. After all, since a bolt-action is so slow there's no chance for a second shot, you bet a hunter's going to try his best to make the first shot count. Now that's innovation. However, just in case you are hunting three-toed sloth, and do have time for a follow-up shot, the Model 190 comes with a two-round box magazine.

The gun comes chambered for the awesomely powerful 16 gauge 2 3/4" shot shells, or if the hunter wants even less power, it will accept 2" or 2 1/4 inch ammunition.


Mossberg, vintage, bot-action, shotgun, 1950s, Michigan Upland Hunting, 
Innovative vice-grip operated choke
At the other end of the 26" barrel is the variable C-Lect-Choke that allows the hunter to change the choke from Improved Cylinder to Full Choke with just a few twists of the wrist (or vice-grips if you're not Chuck Norris). This adjustable choke is so far ahead of its time there isn't another gun manufacturer that uses it. Well, actually, Mossberg stopped using it sometime in the 1960s, too, I think.

But perhaps the most innovative feature of this gun is its weight. While original company advertising materials claim it weighs a mere 6 1/4 lbs., that is at the beginning of the day. This gun has the amazing ability to get heavier as the day goes on. This feature is especially handy (pardon the pun) to hunters with freakishly short arms, as after carrying this gun a couple days, their arms will be measureably longer. Normal hunters, however, may need to buy shoes with thicker soles to keep their knuckles from dragging

title: For Sale/Trade:  R.H. Ruana Knives
postcontent:
I have two of these bad boys for sale. There is so much history in these knives, their maker, and the company. Feel free to read up on it. These are both stamped "RH Ruana," signifying they are originals made by the man, Rudy, himself. All new knives made by his grandsons are stamped with "Ruana." These are/were made by hand in Bonner, MT. The steel used is some of the easiest to sharpen, but they hold their edge better than any knife I have owned. my dad has one that he skinned and gutted 4 elk with in one day, because all the other knives in the group went down with broken blades or dull blades.  Feel free to IM me if you have any questions! I have a few more photos available too.

First one has Rudy's bullwhip signature on the blade dated 1983. The blade measures 3.5" and is 7.25" overall. No nicks in the blade, and it is in awesome shape. Obvious signs of wear from its age, but she's in excellent shape. includes the original leather sheath. I believe this is one of the earlier skinner models. $600 shipped 

Second is a slightly smaller skinner model. The blade measures 3.5" and is 6.25" overall. This is an original made by Rudy as well, but it looks brand new. I don't believe it has ever even been sharpened except from the factory. Asking $500 shipped

title: For Sale/Trade:  Custom CZ-52 w/ Novak Target Sights and ammo
postcontent:
PRICE DROP for quick sale. Will be put back in the safe after Friday if not sold. This fine single-action handgun was made in 1954 and imported in the early 90's (no import marks). Included are three magazines with aftermarket extended floorplates for fast reloads, the original holster, and the option to include 520 rounds of ammo. The CZ-52 is widely accepted to be a more robust design than the TT-33, utilizing the roller delayed-blowback action like the MG-42, HK G3, and MP5. The original rollers have been replaced with new hardened steel ones. The original firing pin has also been replaced with a hardened steel model that won't break when dry fired. The original tiny fixed sights were milled off and 1911 style Novak adjustable target sights installed- the difference is amazing compared to the factory sights. The original Bakelite grips were sealed and then painted black. The parkerized finish on the frame is in 90%+ original  condition and the slide has been coated in Dark Parkerizing Gray Alumahyde II rustproof gun coating (properly cured) so it can be carried IWB without worrying about rusting from sweat. Function wise, I have never had any malfunction in 500 rounds. The decocker/safety works properly and the hammer does not contact the firing pin when decocking.

It fires the potent 7.62x25mm tokarev round which will defeat both sides of a threat level IIa bullet proof vest or one side of a level II vest with normal target grade FMJ's. The now banned 320 (of 520) hardened steel core AP rounds I am including will defeat all soft body armor up to level III. These rounds are legal to own in all 50 states, they can just no longer be imported into the country or manufactured.

The gun has a very thin profile and can be concealed as easily and sometimes better than a 1911. If you're expecting bad guys with body armor and want better penetration than a .357 SIG, this is the gun for you. Would make a perfect glove box gun to shoot through glass and sheet metal if needed to. Hollow points are available online if you are concerned about over-penetration.

The ammo available is:
100 rounds of banned Norinco mild steel core non-corrosive FMJ
100 rounds of S&B indoor range safe new production non-corrosive reloadable FMJ
320 rounds of mixed Hintenberger and another European manufacture 1955 and 1962 production hardened steel core AP. The finest 7.62 ammo ever available to civilians, last available in 1990. This ammo is mildly corrosive like most surplus stuff. It is very clean brass cased and berdan primed. I have shot through 1/4" steel plate like it wasn't there, and I have seen it shred Kevlar helmets.

Besides defense, this is one heck of a fun gun to shoot. It sounds like a .44 magnum going off, and it has the recoil of a .45 1911. Minute of bad guy accuracy out to 150 yards from a bench, and very flat shooting. 9mm luger drop-in conversion barrels are available online.

I'm looking for a new toy, so this one has to go. 

$400 cash for the pistol and three mags and holster.
$600 cash OBO for the above plus all the ammo.

Ammo is not for sale without the gun.

The sights, modern steel upgrades, and magazines are worth $400 alone.

I am open to trades and trades plus cash for firearms and military related equipment, silver, cool stuff etc. What do you have? Worst I can say is no thanks. I am NOT interested in your used SCUBA gear, marijuana grow lights, or fish tanks.

If you are reading this, it's still for sale. 

Will meet at the Tulalip Cabelas in Marysville, WA only. Will ship overnight to your FFL at your expense for $50. Ammo ships separately for $20. 

I am a CPL holder and will only sell to US citizens 18 and older with valid ID and bill of sale. If you have a CPL or WAC card, no bill of sale is necessary.

Thank you for looking, and remember to vote no on I-594 this November.

PSB-AR-FDE Pistol Stabilizing Brace
****** Color is Flat Dark Earth / FDE ********** 

SIG SAUER® introduces the SB15 Pistol Stabilizing Brace, a shooter's aid that is designed to improve the single-handed shooting performance of buffer tube equipped pistols. 

This veteran-designed and U.S.-manufactured accessory enhances accuracy and reduces felt recoil when using an AR-style pistol. 

Made from high-quality, elasto-polymer, the SB15 is manufactured to close tolerances and fits all pistols equipped with an AR-style buffer tube 1.0" - 1.2" in diameter. 

The Pistol Stabilizing Brace uses the operator's forearm to provide stable support, thereby minimizing accuracy-robbing spin and shift. 

A flexible cuff with two adjustable nylon straps allows the SB15 to be custom fit to any user. 

* ATF has reviewed this product and determined that attaching the SB15 to a firearm does not alter the classification of the firearm or subject the firearm to NFA control. 

A portion of the proceeds from the sale of every SB15 Pistol Stabilizing Brace goes to support the veterans of HAVA (Honored American Veterans Afield).

Miami Shooters Club provides such a course with its team of NRA certified instructors - who will teach students the important fundamentals of how to safely use a semi-automatic pistol and revolver. Your concealed weapons permit will allow you to concealed carry in more than 30 states.

Miami Shooters Club's instructors carry multiple certifications under the NRA, have traveled abroad to train and receive firearm certifications, and are hand-to-hand self defense experts - having taught multiple seminars for the Miami Dade Police department. Under their instruction in the concealed carry class, students will learn the mechanisms behind pistols and how they operate while learning how to grip the firearm, aim, pull the trigger, get into a proper stance, and much more. The class 
also covers many of the legal issues and expected ethics of concealed carry in Florida. The classes are designed for complete beginners who have never touched a gun before... but experienced shooters will learn something as well.

At the end of the classroom portion, students will safely discharge a pistol under the supervision of a certified instructor, as required by the State of Florida. 

Miami Shooters Club will provide a firearm, ammunition, eye protection, and ear protection at no extra cost.

Classes take place in Miami on Fridays at 6:30pm or on Saturdays at 1pm.

Call now at 305-225-4610 or send an email to info@FFAgyms.com with your name and phone number for more information.

Looking for a good deep carry gun? Look no further. Up for sale is my Sig P238 Nitron .380ACP

Everyone is pretty familiar with the P238s, they are based on Colts design, in fact it IS Colts design but was sold to SIG. They are available with regular sights or night sights, and this particular pistol does have the SIGLITE night sights. The "Nitron" name is not just a fancy name for an all black pistol, but rather Nitron is the name of Sigs proprietary finish that is on this model. It is an ion bonding finish which means it actually chemically bonds to the metals, it does not just coat them like a Cerakote or Duracoat. This makes it more durable, and nearly impossible to simply scratch. This finish will hold up for years, even with every day carry.
This particular gun has had just enough rounds through it to break it in an ensure its reliability. Around 200 or so. Runs like a top, absolutely no issues.

title: For Sale:  Winchester Trapper 94 Saddle Ring Carbine in .44 Mag; LIKE NEW
postcontent:
I have a Winchester 94 in .44 Magnum that I purchased new over 20 years ago.  It has been in the climate-controlled gun safe it's whole life, with no wear or damage.  This is the short barreled carbine with the saddle ring and deluxe walnut stock.  I would call it 99%+, with no damage, dings, dents or anything bad that I can see.  It has always been wrapped in a gun sock, and never left dirty to corrode.  The gun is completely stock, with no modifications.  This is the AE series, angle eject, so you can mount a scope on it.  The receiver is drilled and tapped for a scope rings, with the mounting holes still retaining the threaded "plugs".  Also comes with the original manual and a schematic/parts catalog.  I believe the carbine is as close to "new" as you would be likely to find!  I have fired it a few times over the years, probably under 150 rounds.  It shoots .44 special as well, with almost no felt recoil. It is really fun to shoot and just feels really solid in your hands.  It's all steel, no cheap aluminum in the receivers like the some of the reproduction 94's.  And best of all it's made in the USA!  

Some attributes of the Winchester 1894:

- The Winchester Model 1894 was the first commercial repeating rifle built to be used with smokeless powder.  The action is inherently strong, smooth and dependable.

- The Winchester 1894 holds the record for best-selling high-powered rifle in U.S. history.

- Lots of steel and wood. It's just made the old fashioned way. Lots of durable steel parts that feel solid and reliable.

- Incredible design. John Moses Browning really outdid himself when he designed the Model 94. The mechanism is smooth and precise. The ergonomics are practically perfect. The action is strong and simply not prone to wearing out.

- Solid lockup. The John Browning design was created to handle the newest type of ammunition in the world at the time: smokeless powder loads. And it is still handling them. The Model 94 has been chambered in some of the meanest calibers ever developed for fast action in brusy conditions.

- It's a lifetime gun. Some rifles come and go, but a Model 94 just builds a lifetime of memories. It is one gun that your family will appreciate long after you are gone. It's a gun your great grandson will learn to shoot with. Timeless.  

- Unfortunately, after 112 years, production ceased in 2006.

Please e-mail me with your phone number if you want to come take a look. I'm located in North Skagit County, but I travel south to Seattle from time to time. I'm going to want to see a CWP and ID for the private transfer.

I'm not really looking for any trades at this time, but it never hurts to ask! Thanks for looking, and have a great day!

title: For Sale:  Maryland Concealed Carry Permit Training (initial and renewal) 02-21&22-2015
postcontent: All American Small Arms Training will offer a training course for a Maryland State Concealed Carry (handgun) Permit. The training course will be conducted on February 21 and February 22 2015 (weather permitting) from 8:00am-4:00pm in Bowie Maryland for all who wish to obtain a Concealed Carry Permit in Maryland. The duration of the training course, is 16 hours for an initial permit application, and 8 hours for a renewal application. The training course will include intensive firearm safety procedures in general and during various aspects of daily routine and practice, legal responsibilities and requirements including use of deadly force and the morals, statutes and precedent concerned. Also included is nomenclature, cartridge structure and function, projectile selection, sight alignment, position shooting, use of cover and concealment, dry-fire practice, and live fire range practical applications and final qualifications. Instructor is Maryland State Police Licensed and Certified, NRA Certified, a veteran of military service, and an accomplished competitive shooter. The training course is open to anyone not legally disqualified from owning, possessing, or being in contact with firearms. Taking and passing this training course does NOT guarantee you will be issued a Concealed Carry Permit in the state of Maryland or any other state or jurisdiction. This training course is for an initial permit application but permit renewal applicants can and will be included; contact instructor for details. Initial permit application training is $350.00, and renewal permit application training is $175.00. Security Guards may also attend this training and certification course, with the only difference being the live-fire course of fire. Pre-registration is mandatory. title: For Trade:  FEG SMC-918 9x18 Makarov
postcontent:
I'm posting for trade a pretty hard to acquire handgun. It is an FEG (Hungarian) SMC-918 9x18 Makarov. For you Makarov collectors, this is a must have. It is in 98% condition as you can see in the detailed pics (tiny little gouge on the raised thumb rest on the grips). The bluing is in EXCELLENT condition, mirror like if i may.
Some info on the handgun:
-They are a variant of the Walther PPK, with some changes to the safeties and an aluminum frame.
-Chambered in 9x18 Makarov, 6+1 capacity
-They are the smallest pistol chambered in 9x18 MAK imported into the US
-Pretty much the same design as the FEG PA-63s that are available, but with a shorter barrel and a shorter grip.
-It is a more recent production of the FEG RK-59.
-Very few of these were imported into the states

In the pics, I have it next to a M&P9 Shield to compare the size. This is most definitely a pocket carry gun.

Not looking to sell, just looking what people have to offer in a trade, I'm perfectly fine with keeping the firearm if nothing really comes my way.

Comes with 2 6rd mags, original box and paperwork, and 50rds of Tula 94gr FMJ.

FTF in or around Southside Indy/Beech Grove area.

Thanks for looking.
